SessionedTextBox.name: Label
SessionedTextBox.htmlText:
Lowell (Massachusetts) Foreclosures

This visualization provides a variety of information about foreclosures in Lowell during the period from 2005 to 2010, a period during which the housing market showed extreme turbulence. The bar graph at the bottom of the page shows the number of foreclosures in the current year, the total number of foreclosures over the 5-year period, and the number of orders-of-notice in the current year (an order-of-notice is a preliminary step taken prior to actual foreclosure). Select the current year using the time-slider tool on the right above the bar chart. Each bar represents a census tract, and the bars are organized according to the neighborhood in which the census tract is found. Note that in 2005, there were very few foreclosures and some orders of notice. Moving forward in time we see that both foreclosures and orders-of-notice increased in the next three years, with a peak being reached in the Centralville neighborhood in 2008. After that, foreclosures declined.

The map in the upper left-hand corner shows Lowell's neighborhoods, which are made up of census tracts. Overlaid on the census tracts are dots that represent the actual locations of foreclosures, and these dots are color-coded to differentiate the years in which the foreclosures occurred. Each of these annual sets of points is an independent "map layer", so that they can be turned on and off independently. The map also includes a layer showing parcel boundaries, which is currently turned off.

The scatterplot in the upper right corner plots two demographic indicators from the US Census against each other, the proportion of persons of Hispanic or Latino origin versus the proportion of the population that is poor or near-poor. The color of the dots represents the number of foreclosures in the current year, and the size of the dot represents the percentage of owner-occupied housing units. Note that the scatterplot simultaneously shows four variables in relationship to each other.

The legend to the right of the map shows the level of foreclosures in the current year for the current census tract. You can select a census tract by moving the mouse pointer over the tract's bar in the bar graph or its dot in the scatterplot.
